\begin_layout Chapter
The Saurian War
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expansion of humankind into the galaxy was largely peaceful in the early
 years.
 With the Great Plague having wiped clear much of the sentient life in the
 galaxy prior to humanity's emergence, the biggest threats to exploration
 were only from the horrors left behind by the plague, or rogue elements
 from human civilization in the form of claim-jumpers and pirates.
 The few sapient races encountered generally proved friendly, either in
 the midst of their own exploration phase themselves or simply eager for
 new friends in a lonely and hostile universe.
 The discovery of these new species gave new hope that the galaxy might
 not be a complete void of other intelligent life despite the ravages of
 the Plague, and new effort was expended especially towards seeking out
 new civilizations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, humanity and its new allies were soon to face their first great
 challenger.
 Someone else was hunting the stars, not for friends, but for humanity itself.
 They were seeking Earth, and they meant to claim it for their own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Saurians
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Millions of years ago, on the eve of the asteroid impact that would trigger
 the last great extinction event of Earth's prehistory, a desperate plan
 was hatched.
 
\emph on
Arcanoraptor, 
\emph default
a young species of sapient theropods constructs a series of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

seed pods
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which will bear forth across the galaxy in an attempt to save their species
 from extinction.
 Unable to construct a large enough vessel with enough supplies for ongoing
 life, instead the arcanoraptors store eggs from their best and brightest
 in stasis, only to be hatched once they pod itself has landed on a planet
 with suitable atmosphere.
 On each pod is a plaque, engraved with information about the destinations
 of each other pod of dozens launched, along with coordinates for Earth's
 sun.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the pods do not survive, and even those that do take millions of
 years to arrive at their destination.
 While the pod and the eggs themselves provide just enough nutrients for
 the hatching arcanoraptors to survive initially, only their own wits will
 allow them to survive beyond this point.
 Their civilization is lost, preserved only in the information inscribed
 within the capsules, and the cataclysm that wiped out most life on earth
 larger than small mammals and birds erased almost any trace of this lost
 space-faring society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hurtling through space at a speed barely faster than the earliest human
 deep space probes, the pods survived the ravages of the Great Plague largely
 through obscurity.
 Most missed their marks, or were destroyed by other forces.
 Some did survive, however.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One pod thrived above all, and managed to rebuild a new civilization with
 remarkable haste.
 Landing on the second planet of a small yellow sun not unlike our own,
 the newborn hatchlings found fertile soil, plentiful food, and a large
 single continent not unlike the Pangaea they had left behind on Earth.
 Eventually, one tribe would unite the scattered survivors, and thus the
 Rax Empire was born.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Hunt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its internal conflicts resolved, the Rax Empire set about looking inward
 into their own forgotten history.
 They re-discovered the lost seed pod that placed them on their world, and
 this piece of their lost heritage came to be held with religious reverence.
 Rax scholars would study the words and inscriptions of their lost ancestors
\emph on
 
\emph default
for generations.
 As their society grew and advanced to the space age they made it their
 mission to unite the other survivors of Earth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This continual mission would come to be known as The Hunt, and would remain
 the uniting drive for the species as it expanded into the rest of the galaxy
 around Rax Prime.
 The Hunt eventually re-united many of the lost surviving descendants of
 the seed pods, and through this reunification the Great Rax Empire became
 a galactic power to rival the expansion of humanity, making their eventual
 contact that much more inevitable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was a Surveyor team that first encountered the Rax.
 A first-time crew with a fresh claim, the 
\emph on
GSS Mauve-Taupe
\emph default
 exited subspace just outside the Gamma Orionis system, directly in the
 path of an oncoming Rax freight hauler.
 After considerable confusion and panic on both sides, the two sides managed
 to avoid conflict long enough for the 
\emph on
Mauve-Taupe
\emph default
's science officer to translate the incoming terrified chatter from the
 Rax ship and talk both sides down from a potentially embarrassing incident.
 The 
\emph on
Mauve-Taupe 
\emph default
was then directed to Gamma Orionis IV, a small and rocky world hosting a
 Rax mining colony, to introduce themselves to the local colonial administrator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Met with a warm welcome at first by the local authorities, the conversation
 quickly turned sour when one of the 
\emph on
Mauve-Taupe
\emph default
's crew, a human engineer, explained where he was from.
 The administrator quickly made the connection between the human homeworld
 and that spoken of in the ancient pod text, and grew more and more furious.
 Taking disgusted offense at the very idea of a bunch of egg-eating, mammal-desc
endants claiming residence of their holy ancestral grounds, he ordered the
 lot arrested.
 The crew of the 
\emph on
Mauve-Taupe
\emph default
 managed to escape capture only through use of a barely functioning teleport
 bay and a slow reaction on the part of the Rax station's port authority.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They reported only of a hostile exchange with an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unknown saurian species
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (the science officer's translator failed to understand the term 'Rax' as
 a name for the species, and they continue to be largely known as 'Saurians'
 in Tradespeak).
 The report simply advised avoiding that space until more formal diplomatic
 ties could be established.
 Thanks to this understated report and the inevitable bureaucratic delays
 involved in Guild report processing, humanity was thus initially unaware
 that it had just started an interstellar war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
War
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
News of Earth's survival and habitability was quickly sent upwards to the
 Holy Rax Emperor, who formally declared war on the human species and the
 intent of the Rax Empire to reclaim its ancestral homeland.
 Skirmishes and raids on outlying colonies began not long after, and soon
 the known galaxy was embroiled in the largest conflict in human history.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the front roared on, humanity called on its friends and allies to bolster
 their numbers against the highly organized and at times brutal Saurian
 armada, even recruiting from among newly discovered pre-starfaring peoples
 in exchange for membership in the growing Human Alliance.
 The first androids also found their way into service across the fleets
 of the Alliance, and the Surveyor's Guild became a vital part of the war
 effort as well.
 Exploration priority was placed on locating valuable raw materials and
 new technology that could supply the front and provide an edge to the Alliance
 in the ongoing conflict.
\end_layout

