\begin_layout Chapter
Characters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exploration of a galaxy in a state of war is a different prospect than that
 of one in relative peace-time.
 While the threat of rogue elements has always been a part of a surveyor's
 job, and the ruins of the ancients remain ever filled with hazards and
 horrors galore, the realities of life during the Saurian War lead to new
 faces and new skill sets finding their way into the ranks of the Guild.
 The following chapter presents some new options for existing classes, as
 well as new classes entirely, for player characters during and after the
 Saurian War.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Improving Saves and Abilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hulks and Horrors 
\emph default
classes are designed with the expectation that all characters are at least
 minimally trained in the full range of expected abilities for a surveyor
 or explorer.
 The classes are thus designed more as chosen careers, and like in any job,
 there can be good or bad examples of the field.
 The more important consideration in design thus was making characters vary
 widely, and allowing every character to try any action (this is also why
 there are few 'exclusive' abilities in 
\emph on
H&H 
\emph default
classes).
 Some gamers however may prefer more sharply defined classes that better
 guarantee a stronger level of competence at the classâs particular talents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optionally then, you may consider allowing class abilities and saves to
 improve with level.
 This will allow distinction between classes to improve as each class becomes
 more experienced at its own particular set of skills.
 Under this rule, class abilities that provide a +1 to specific stat checks
 (including saves), now improve by a further +1 at levels 3 and 6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Combat Pilots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the outbreak of the Saurian War, more and more pilots are cutting their
 teeth in the field of battle rather than threading through the debris fields
 of Dyson Prime.
 Pilots trained in the combat forces who find themselves no longer qualified
 for duty, unable to cope with the stress of the battlefield, or simply
 too free-spirited for military service often turn to Guild work instead
 as surveyors.
 Such combat-trained pilots are increasingly in demand as well, as skirmishes
 between Alliance and Saurian forces in unexplored sectors continue.
 Each side in the war is eager to hunt down new resources and new technologies
 to bring to the front, and this means ship-to-ship combat is an expected
 hazard in the uncharted reaches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pilots wishing to take a more combat-oriented specialty can optionally exchange
 their 
\emph on
Daredevil 
\emph default
ability for a new talent, 
\emph on
Combat Pilot
\emph default
.
 This replaces the pilot classâs knack for barnstorming heroics, for skill
 at keeping their ship a difficult target to track in a fight.
 The details of this new ability are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
Combat
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Ace:
\series default
\emph default
 The combat pilot is an expert at dodging and maneuvering a ship through
 heavy enemy fire, able to thread their vessel through the fray with precision
 unrivaled.
 When called upon to make any piloting roll in combat, the combat pilot
 may choose to roll 2D20, and keep the highest result.
 If they succeed, the maneuver is successful as usual but the ship gains
 a further -1AC until the next round.
 If they fail, however, they have lost control of the ship, and no maneuvering
 rolls can be attempted until control is regained, leaving the ship at +2AC
 until a DEX check is passed (combat ace cannot be used on this check.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Soldier MOS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior to the Saurian War, few soldiers saw combat with any regularity.
 Most tended to remain in the service as career soldiers in sleepy garrisons
 or administrative desks, or muster out into civilian careers.
 Those veterans who were willing to volunteer for a surveyor crew tended
 to be from special operations and quarantine units, who had seen combat
 against plague horrors and worse, and thus were relatively more willing
 to sign on for the dangerous life of an explorer and hulk hunter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the War however, a greater variety of former military personnel have
 found themselves out of military work, having been injured, declared unfit,
 or even deserted.
 There is thus a greater variety in the specialties of those soldiers finding
 work on surveyor teams.
 As well, those groups wishing to run military campaigns focused directly
 on the action of the war, may wish to be able to portray the broader range
 of talents possible within the soldier class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better portray this diversity, soldiers may choose to exchange
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Covert Ops
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 ability of the class for one of the following Military Occupational Specialties
 (or MOS).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Armored This soldier was employed in the armored division, operating land
 vehicles from transports to tanks.
 the character has a +1 to stat checks involving the operation of land vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Exo-Armor The soldier was a member of an exo-armor unit, trained in the
 operation of powered armor suits.
 The character has a +1 to-hit with hardpoint mounted weapons, and may purchase
 a basic exo-armor (AC1) for half price at character creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Gunnery The soldier served as an artillery officer, tank gunner, or other
 heavy gun operator.
 They have a +1 to-hit with mounted weapons and artillery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Infantry The character was a basic ground-pounder, marching through the
 fields of some god-awful rock.
 They've developed considerable stamina for forced marches, gaining a +1
 to CON for saves against fatigue when travelling on foot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Logistics Not the most exciting career in the armed forces, but a vital
 one, the soldier served as part of the logistical or supply division.
 A life of navigating military bureacracy for supplies has made them a shrewd
 bargainer: they pay 10% less for equipment purchases at character creation,
 and they have a +1 to CHA for any negotiations involving trade transactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Marine The soldier is a true space marine, a front-line hardened invader
 and shipboard combat expert.
 Marines count zero gravity as a favored environment, and their gung-ho
 attitude gives them a +1 to DEX for the purpose of initiative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Marksman The soldier is a designated marksman or sniper, trained in expert
 accuracy at considerable distance.
 The soldier has a +1 to-hit with rifles, and may attack targets up to 300
 yards distant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Mechanic The soldier worked in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

motor pool
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 repairing vehicles.
 They have a +1 to INT for the purposes of repairing land and air vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Recon The character served in a recon or patrol unit, requiring them to
 travel quickly through unknown or difficult terrain and provide accurate
 information about enemy positions.
 The soldier and their group suffer half the usual penalties when traversing
 difficult terrain, and the recon soldier gains a -1 to AC while in such
 terrain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Survival Further deep recon units and even individual scouts are sometimes
 deployed.
 The soldier has recieved extensive training on surviving with limited equipment
 in hostile terrain, and gain a +1 to WIS checks to locate food and water
 in the surrounding area.
 On a successful check and with 1d4 hours' time, the soldier finds sufficient
 food and water for themselves to survive another day.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Engineer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part technical wizard and part handyman, engineers are masters of maintenance,
 experts at engines, and triumphant troubleshooters.
 Engineers are absolutely indispensable to keeping a good ship running,
 and just as handy planet-side when it comes time to quickly repair broken
 equipment, puzzle out some piece of alien tech, or just keep everyone's
 guns and other implements of destruction fully functioning at their peak
 efficiency.
 A good engineer should have a high INT, the better to perform their repairs,
 and usually possesses a pretty high DEX as well, and often decent STR,
 both handy attributes to have on the job, as both dexterity and even raw
 strength come in handy in the line of work for a ship's engineer.
\end_layout

