\begin_layout Chapter
Robots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the war dragged on, shortages in trained manpower became an issue across
 the Alliance, leading to a sudden interest in intelligent robots.
 While simple 'dumb' robots were widely in use by most of the Alliance species,
 full artificial intelligence was another matter.
 The Treaty of Durandal IV prohibited the use of disembodied human-comparable
 artificial intelligences among all signatory species after a series of
 particularly disastrous incidents involving AI, one of which nearly started
 an interstellar war, and another of which wiped out an entire research
 colony by flooding it with hallucinogenic gas after the AI became bored.
 Apparently, giving a digital entity with more intelligence than an entire
 physics department nearly limitless computational capacity and a complete
 lack of physical interaction or limitation has an unavoidable tendency
 to result in their breaking out into megalomania and genocidal rage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
S.T.E.V.E.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fortunately for the Canis Majoris Cybernetics Corporation, however, this
 left a loophole.
 An AI system could be developed so long as it was contained solely within
 a physical body with sufficiently limited processing capacity.
 So, following on the initial success of their previous animal-analogue
 products like M.U.L.E.
 and H.O.R.S.E., CMCC began developing the Synthetic Technoid for Engineering,
 Violence, and Exploration, or 'S.T.E.V.E.'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
S.T.E.V.E.'s design is heavily informed by the limitations of the Treaty.
 In addition to possessing a simpler electronic brain that limits it to
 roughly the same range of intelligence as a human save for some computational
 tasks, S.T.E.V.E.
 was a landmark development in non-deterministic AI.
 Every S.T.E.V.E.
 is designed to develop independently and randomly from the moment of it's
 virtual birth, and as a result, none is ever quite the same as another.
 This fundamental incompatibility makes it nearly impossible for more than
 one S.T.E.V.E.
 to ever share resources or combine programming, thus preventing any further
 Durandal IV-level incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flipside of this of course is that the process has certain ...
 quirks.
 Perhaps owing to the narcissistic personality of the original project manager
 (the name 'S.T.E.V.E.' is actually a backronym for his name), or to flaws in
 the fractal formula that generates the AI code, S.T.E.V.E.
 displays certain trends in its behavioral development.
 While every unit is different and they are more than competent employees,
 S.T.E.V.E.s have a reputation for being particularly obstinate, sarcastic, and
 surly.
 One can always count on S.T.E.V.E.
 to do what it's told, but it is significantly more to ask to expect it
 to necessarily be happy about it, and rarely will it do so without a smart
 remark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than being a liability, however, this 'feature' helped to humanize
 S.T.E.V.E.
 to its fellow crew members, and proved especially popular with military
 and surveyor crews.
 S.T.E.V.E.'s willfulness was occasionally frustrating, but its sense of humor
 proved popular with the fatalistic attitudes of people who regularly risk
 being devoured by giant space worms or atomized in spacial anomalies.
 While later development produced models with more agreeable personalities,
 S.T.E.V.E.
 remains popular with surveyors despite, or perhaps even because of, these
 quirks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast to S.T.E.V.E.'s colorful personality, the robot's appearance could
 not be more workmanlike.
 Built on a simple humanoid frame with outer metallic shell, the S.T.E.V.E.
 unit is manufactured from recycled aerospace materials to minimize both
 cost and weight.
 The standard shell is left as unpainted rust-proof brushed metal, and to
 save further money on complicated and expensive servo motors, the head
 foregoes an articulated facial structure for a simple LED matrix display
 that animates its facial expressions.
 Other than the serial number and bar code stamped on the upper right chest
 and along the upper arms, it can be difficult to tell one S.T.E.V.E.
 from another, and this confusion is only amplified by the tendency of handlers
 to not bother changing it from its default name.
 This has been known to create routine confusion when someone makes the
 mistake of calling for 'Steve' on spaceport PA systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the economical construction, however, S.T.E.V.E.
 is a durable and versatile companion for a surveyor.
 As robotic lifeform, it functions efficiently and safely in nearly all
 environments without need for filter masks, rebreathers, or additional
 air supply.
 The armored shell is designed to withstand extremes of both heat and cold
 without significant loss in function, as well as withstand significant
 physical stress and damage without loss of function.
 The adaptive AI and built-in redundancies further help keep the robot in
 top function as much as is possible.
 Its fuel consumption needs are both minimal and flexible, requiring only
 a small daily weight of natural or synthetic hydrocarbons to provide a
 catalyst for its power cells.
 The base AI seed for each S.T.E.V.E.
 unit is preconfigured with a primer on the basics of combat, starship maintenan
ce, and space exploration, though individual aptitudes in some fields will
 vary based on how the AI develops.
 An adaptive machine interface port allows the robot to directly connect
 to and communicate with computerized machinery, and a multi-purpose plasma
 tool allows for defense, cutting, welding, and soldering.
 The result is an indespensible assistant and companion for any surveyor
 crew or military unit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stats
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to their standardized manufacturing, S.T.E.V.E.s do not generate their stats
 in the same manner as normal PCs.
 Variance in capability is minimal within standard manufacturing tolerances,
 but the non-deterministic AI means there can be notable differences in
 personality (CHA).
 Rather than rolling 3d6 across the board as is customary, S.T.E.V.E.s thus generate
 their standard stats from the following standard array, rolling only for
 CHA: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
STR 14, INT 12, WIS 10, DEX 11, CON 15, CHA 3d6
\end_layout

