Skin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 These shells are designed less for protection and durability than for appearanc
e and verisimilitude.
 Skins offer little physical protection, but can be made from human or alien
 analogue materials that create for a more believable appearance for android-typ
e models.
 Skins may also be employed for the weight advantage, particularly for combat
 units specializing in stealth.
 Skinned robots may wear regular armor (all types), which offers certain
 advantages in utility and maintenance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Commercial A basic commercial-grade shell, offering basic protection against
 wear-and-tear and minor knocks and dings.
 The robot ignores the first point of any damage recieved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Industrial Industrial quality alloy shells provide the kind of durability
 normally reserved for heavy equipment.
 The shell provides protection against extreme environments and temperatures
 from -200 to +600 degrees F, and ignores the first 2 points of damage taken.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Military This shell is rated as full combat grade, able to withstand significant
 small arms fire and keep on ticking.
 The armor is also shielded against EMP attack, and ignores the first 3
 points of damage taken from any source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Exo This shell is designed to go toe-to-toe with exo-armors, a top-grade
 hardened shell able to wade through a withering amount of weapons fire
 in combat scenarios.
 The shell is fully environment protected, can withstand temperatures from
 -200 to +600 degrees F, and ignores the first 4 points of damage taken.
\end_layout

